            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Rohan Sharma-Klein is a product of two distinct, yet complementary, worlds. Raised in Berkeley by his mother, a literature professor from New Delhi, and his father, a Jewish-American architect, Rohan\u2019s childhood was a blend of Diwali celebrations, Hanukkah dinners, and constant discussions about structure, society, and place. His bicultural upbringing instilled in him an early appreciation for how different systems\u2014be they cultural or structural\u2014could coexist and intertwine. A formative trip to India at age 16 was a turning point; witnessing Delhi's chaotic yet vibrant human flow ignited a passion for untangling the complexities of urban movement.\n\nThis passion guided his educational journey. After earning an undergraduate degree at UC Berkeley, he pursued a master\u2019s in Urban Planning, focusing on transportation. He began his career as a junior planner for a Bay Area transit authority, meticulously analyzing commuter data and advocating for safer bike infrastructure. Rohan\u2019s data-driven, human-centered approach earned him respect, and he steadily rose through the ranks. Now, as a Director of Urban Mobility Strategy, he shapes high-level policy, working to integrate everything from bike-share programs and delivery drones to public transit into a cohesive, equitable network.\n\nRohan\u2019s life is a practical application of his professional philosophy. He and his long-term partner, a landscape designer named Chloe, live in a thoughtfully designed flat in the Inner Sunset. His 3.8-mile commute is the highlight of his morning; he glides his e-bike through the crisp fog of Golden Gate Park, feeling the city\u2019s rhythm firsthand. He sees his commute not just as travel, but as daily fieldwork.\n\nSocially, his circle consists of other civic-minded professionals\u2014architects, public health officials, and non-profit leaders. Their dinner conversations often revolve around solving the city's intractable problems. Rohan dreams of a future San Francisco where transportation is so seamless and sustainable that private car ownership becomes an afterthought. His ultimate aspiration isn't a higher title, but to leave behind a tangible legacy: a city that moves better, for everyone."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers being nine, his architect father showing him how to build their Hanukkah menorah out of scrap metal and wood from his workshop. His father explained the balance of a cantilevered branch, while his mother lit the first candle and spoke of the story behind the light. Rohan felt a profound sense of rightness, seeing how a physical structure and a cultural story could become one. It was the first time he understood that everything, even faith, had a design, and that design had a soul.\n\n2.\nStanding at an intersection in Old Delhi at sixteen, the sensory overload was total: the hazy heat, the scent of fried samosas, the cacophony of horns. He watched, mesmerized, as a family of five on a single scooter wove gracefully through a seemingly impenetrable wall of auto-rickshaws and cars. There was no visible system, yet there was a deep, intuitive logic. In that moment of awe, the chaos became a beautiful, complex dance. This was the puzzle he knew he had to spend his life trying to understand.\n\n3.\nFresh out of grad school, he spent months advocating for a protected bike lane on a treacherous street. After its approval, he stood in a light drizzle one evening, just to watch. He saw a young commuter, her face tense with concentration, ride down the new green lane. As she passed, she glanced over and gave a small, almost imperceptible nod of thanks. That tiny gesture of recognition felt more significant than any promotion, cementing his belief that data\u2019s true purpose was to make one person\u2019s journey safer.\n\n4.\nHe and Chloe were on one of their first dates, walking through the newly opened Salesforce Park. He was explaining the pedestrian flow patterns from the transit center below when she stopped him, pointing to a specific shrub. She detailed its drought tolerance and how its silver leaves would catch the afternoon light. He saw in her the same passion for living systems that he had for engineered ones. It was then he knew their lives would fit together, two complementary blueprints for a more thoughtful world.\n\n5.\nJust last week, gliding through Golden Gate Park on his morning commute, he paused at an intersection. A new Muni hybrid bus hissed to a stop, a peloton of cyclists flowed past, and a food delivery bot patiently waited its turn on the crosswalk. For a brief, perfect moment, every piece moved in harmony\u2014public and private, human and automated. It felt like watching a preview of the future he was working to build. A quiet wave of hope washed over him, affirming that his dream for the city was possible."
